	  <example>
		    <statement.example>
			      <para xmlns="">
            <para.body>The oriented area of the parallelogram spanned by the vectors <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}=(4,0)</latex>
               </math>  and <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{y}=(0,3)</latex>
               </math> is</para.body>
         </para>
			      <math.display xmlns="">
				        <latex>
					
\OriVol(\Vect{x},\Vect{y}) = \det
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
4 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 3
\end{array}
\right] = 12

				</latex>
			      </math.display>
		    </statement.example>
		
		    <answer xmlns="" type="Explanation" version="1">
         <answer.block>
            <answer.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>This agrees with what the theorem on 
				<subordinate>
                        <hot>oriented volume</hot>
                        <crossref>
                           <theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_DetOrientedVolume"/>
                           <info>
						
						                        <para>
                                 <para.body>Look up this theorem</para.body>
                              </para>
					                      </info>
                        </crossref>
                     </subordinate>
				has us expect: the vectors <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                     </math> span a rectangle with edges of length 4 and 3. So its unoriented area is 12. Moreover the pair of vectors <math>
                        <latex>(\Vect{x},\Vect{y})</latex>
                     </math> determine the counterclockwise or positive orientation of the plane. Therefore <math>
                        <latex>\omega(\Vect{x},\Vect{y})=+1</latex>
                     </math>, and this corresponds to the fact that the determinant is positive.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.block.body>
         </answer.block>
      </answer>
	  </example>
	
	
	
	
	  <example>
		    <statement.example>
			      <para xmlns="">
            <para.body>The oriented area of the parallelogram spanned by the vectors <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{u}=(0,5)</latex>
               </math>  and <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{v}=(2,0)</latex>
               </math> is</para.body>
         </para>
			      <math.display xmlns="">
				        <latex>
					
\OriVol(\Vect{x},\Vect{y}) = \det
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
0 &amp; 2 \\
5 &amp; 0
\end{array}
\right] = -10

				</latex>
			      </math.display>
		    </statement.example>
		
		    <answer xmlns="" type="Explanation" version="1">
         <answer.block>
            <answer.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>This agrees with what the theorem on 
				<subordinate>
                        <hot>oriented volume</hot>
                        <crossref>
                           <theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_DetOrientedVolume"/>
                           <info>
						
						                        <para>
                                 <para.body>Look up this theorem</para.body>
                              </para>
					                      </info>
                        </crossref>
                     </subordinate>
				has us expect: the vectors <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{u}</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
                     </math> span a rectangle with edges of length 5 and 2. So its unoriented area is 10. Moreover the pair of vectors <math>
                        <latex>(\Vect{u},\Vect{v})</latex>
                     </math> determine the clockwise or negative orientation of the plane. Therefore <math>
                        <latex>\omega(\Vect{u},\Vect{v})=-1</latex>
                     </math>, and this corresponds to the fact that the determinant is negative.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.block.body>
         </answer.block>
      </answer>
	  </example>
	
	
	
	
	
	  <example>
		    <statement.example>
			      <para xmlns="">
            <para.body>Find the orientation of <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
               </math> given by the pair of vectors <math>
                  <latex>(\Vect{x},\Vect{y})</latex>
               </math> with <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}=(4320,89)</latex>
               </math> and <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{y}=(4310,87)</latex>
               </math>. </para.body>
         </para>
		    </statement.example>
		    <answer xmlns="" type="Solution" version="1">
         <answer.block>
            <answer.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>The orientation of <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                     </math> given by <math>
                        <latex>(\Vect{x},\Vect{y})</latex>
                     </math> is</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>
					
\omega(\Vect{x},\Vect{y}) = \dfrac{
\det
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
4320 &amp; 4310 \\
89 &amp; 87
\end{array}
\right] }{
\abs{
\det
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
4320 &amp; 4310 \\
89 &amp; 87
\end{array}
\right]
} } = \dfrac{ 375840 - 383590}{\abs{ 375840 - 383590 } } = -1

				</latex>
			            </math.display>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>So the given pair of vectors determines the negative or clockwise orientation of the plane. – Notice that, contrary to the previous two examples, it is not so easy to arrive at this conclusion by ‘inspection’.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.block.body>
         </answer.block>
      </answer>
	  </example>
	
	
	
	
